{"key":"post-12261088","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12261088</id>\n<content>We do something similar to this with shiitake.&amp;nbsp; After full colonization, the 5 pound blocks are removed from the filter patch bags and allowed to dry out on a shelf in a dry room for three weeks.&amp;nbsp; At the end of the drying/browning period, the substrates are soaked 24 hours and put into fruiting conditions.&amp;nbsp; This results in better pinsets and more finished product than the traditional method of introducing to fruiting without the drying cycle.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It also mimics nature in that the substrate dries out during the long hot summer, and then fruits when the fall rains come.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Nice thread.&amp;nbsp; Thanks for posting.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12262019</next>\n<prev>12261011</prev>\n<first>12002751</first>\n<last>26810206</last>\n<when>1269442191</when>\n<utime>03/24/10 05:49 PM</utime>\n</post>"}